   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_C1664_Undated-03_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <name type="place" ref="Id_where"/>
                  <lb/>
                  <date when="1111-06-28"/>June 28. </dateline>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_C1664_Undated-03_page02.jpg"/>
               <salute>
                  Dear Sir
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               You ask whether we or<lb/>
               you should mention the price<lb/>
               of the copy-right of the 4<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>, 5<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> &amp; 6<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>
               <lb/>
               volumes of <title ref="./Workography.xml#Taleo1">Tales of <choice>
                     <orig>Fash.</orig>
                     <reg>Fashionable</reg>
                  </choice> Life</title>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I can assure you that neither<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName> nor <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">I</persName> had or have<lb/>
               formed any opinion upon the<lb/>
               subject nor, do I think, that you<lb/>
               can form a safe: judgement<lb/>
               for some time - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName>'s<lb/>
               name was popular &amp; <choice>
                  <orig>there-<lb/>
               fore</orig>
                  <reg>therefore</reg>
               </choice> there was an early run<lb/>
               for her new publications<lb/>
               Whether, that popularity may<lb/>
               or may not be diminished<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_C1664_Undated-03_page03.jpg"/>

               by her present work, cannot<lb/>
               I should think, be as yet <choice>
                  <orig>de-<lb/>
               termined</orig>
                  <reg>determined</reg>
               </choice> - At all events<lb/>
               you may be assured that we<lb/>
               have the most unbounded<lb/>
               confidence in your justice<lb/>
               &amp; in your honor and that we<lb/>
               shall never name any price<lb/>
               for any thing we send to you<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>It will entertain you to<lb/>
               hear that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName> has been <choice>
                  <orig>re-<lb/>
               proached</orig>
                  <reg>reproached</reg>
               </choice> by some folk<lb/>
               hear for having endeavoured<lb/>
               to <hi rend="underline">lower</hi> the Irish character<lb/>
               I have much more reason<lb/>
               to fear that the English mi<lb/>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_C1664_Undated-03_page04.jpg"/>

               litia should think themselves<lb/>
               aggrieved, or that London<lb/>
               cockneys &amp; Long Acre should<lb/>
               rage against us - or perhaps<lb/>
               the higher frozen circles<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>In all such misfortunes<lb/>
               we keep silence &amp;<lb/>
               depend upon time "the<lb/>
               comforter -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>The idea of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HastF1">Lord Moira</persName>'s<lb/>
               being like <unclear>??vian</unclear> is quite<lb/>
               absurd - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HastF1">Lord Moira</persName> is cer-<lb/>
               tainly a man most <unclear>firm</unclear>
               <lb/>
               of purpose -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>As for <title ref="./Workography.xml#Absen1">Lady Clonbrony</title>, there<lb/>
               are so many &amp; so many<lb/>
               alike, that each will cry<lb/>
               this <unclear>sister</unclear> is levelled at you -<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">
                  <unclear>RLE</unclear>
               </persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <closer>
